    "## 1. Problem Understanding\n",
    "\n",
    "#### What is Customer Churn?\n",
    "**Churn** means a customer stops using a company’s service. For a telecom company, churn happens when a subscriber cancels their phone or internet plan.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Why Do Companies Care About Churn?\n",
    "Acquiring a new customer costs **5–7× more** than retaining an existing one. If a company can identify customers who are *about to leave*, it can offer them discounts, better plans, or improved support — and keep them.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### What Is Machine Learning Doing Here?\n",
    "We have historical data about thousands of customers: their demographics, the services they use, how long they have been customers, and — crucially — whether they eventually churned. A machine-learning model learns **patterns** in this data and then predicts the churn probability for new customers whose outcome we don’t yet know.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### What Does the Final Prediction Represent?\n",
    "We are **not** predicting a simple Yes/No. We are predicting a **probability** between 0 and 1:\n",
    "- 0.05 → the model is quite confident the customer will stay\n",
    "- 0.92 → the model thinks the customer is very likely to churn\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Evaluation Metric — ROC-AUC\n",
    "**ROC-AUC** (Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve) measures how well the model separates churners from non-churners *across all probability thresholds*.\n",
    "- A score of **0.5** means the model is no better than a coin flip.\n",
    "- A score of **1.0** means perfect separation.\n",
    "\n",
    "ROC-AUC is preferred over plain accuracy because our dataset may be **imbalanced** (far more non-churners than churners). A model that always predicts “No churn” could get 73% accuracy but be useless — ROC-AUC catches this.\n",
    "\n",
    "---"
