    "## What This Correlation Matrix Is Telling You\n",
    "\n",
    "A correlation value goes from **-1 to +1**:\n",
    "- **Close to +1** (dark red) = when one goes up, the other goes up too\n",
    "- **Close to -1** (dark blue) = when one goes up, the other goes down\n",
    "- **Close to 0** (white/light) = no real relationship\n",
    "\n",
    "Here's what each number means in plain English:\n",
    "\n",
    "**tenure → Churn = -0.42** (blue)\n",
    "Customers who have been with the company *longer* are *less likely* to churn. Loyalty protects retention. This is your **strongest signal**.\n",
    "\n",
    "**MonthlyCharges → Churn = +0.27** (light red)\n",
    "Customers with *higher bills* are *more likely* to churn. Expensive plans push people away.\n",
    "\n",
    "**TotalCharges → Churn = -0.22** (light blue)\n",
    "Higher total charges means the customer has stayed longer and paid more overall — so they're *slightly less likely* to churn.\n",
    "\n",
    "**SeniorCitizen → Churn = +0.24** (light red)\n",
    "Senior citizens churn a bit more than younger customers.\n",
    "\n",
    "**tenure → TotalCharges = +0.77** (strong red)\n",
    "This just makes logical sense — the longer you stay, the more total money you've paid.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The big takeaway for your model:**\n",
    "> **Tenure** is your most powerful predictor of churn. Long-tenured customers almost never leave. **MonthlyCharges** is the second most important — high bills drive customers away.\n",
    "\n",
